Observations:¶

The typical customer profile appears to be as follows based on the statistics above:

  • The average customer age is approximately 28.7 years with a standard deviation of around 6.94 years,
  • The youngest customer is 18 years and the oldest is 50 years old,
  • The median age is 26 years,
  • The average education level of a customer is approximately 16 years with a standard deviation of 1.6 years,
  • The average customer income level is 53720 with a high standard deviation of approximately 16507,
  • The average usage level is 3.45 with a standard deviation of 1.085,
  • The average fitness level is 3.31 with a standard deviation of 0.96,
  • The average miles per user is 103 but shows a considerable variation with a std. deviation of 51.86
  • When split by product type, there appears to be little difference in the income level, age, education, usage, and fitness levels (average) for TM195 and TM498.

Observations:¶

  • There are three products' that attempt to fit the "Good-Better-Best" product mix,
  • TM195 sells the most, followed by TM498, and TM798,
  • There is little differentiation between TM195 and TM498 in terms of the target group by:
    • age,
    • income,
    • education,
    • miles,
    • and usage.
  • People with higher income levels (>45000 at least), education (> 14 years), and fitness levels prefer TM798
  • Most people who prefere the TM798 tend to be males, with higher income levels, and education levels of 16 - 18 years or greater, with a typical fitness level of 5 and usage at 4 or greater.
  • Most customers are partnered.

Observations:¶

  • Age
    • TM195 is preferred by people between 20 and 30 years of age,
    • Females between ~ 23 - 37 years old tend to prefer the TM195 more than males,
    • TM498 is preferred by people between 20 and 35 years of age,
    • Female customers of the TM498 between 23 and 32 years and between 35 and 45 years outnumber the males,
    • TM798 is bought by people between 20 and 30 years old, and is preferred by males,
  • Income
    • People with incomes between 30000 and 54000 prefer the TM195
    • TM498 is preferred by people with income between 44000 and 54000
    • TM798 is preferred generally by men with incomes between 50000 and 60000, and strongly by males with incomes between 80000 and 95000
  • Education and Usage
    • People with education levels between 16 and 20 years and usage at 4 or above prefer TM798
    • People with education levels of 14 and 16 years and usage greater than 2 prefer the TM195/TM498

Observations:¶

  • There is a strong correlation between Usage and miles, Usage and fitness, and, fitness and miles.
  • There is a good correlation between education and income and some correlation between age and income.
  • Perhaps it would be good to consider replacing usage, fitness, and miles data by some sort of a combined metric.
  • There is a fair correlation between usage/fitness and income as well, and miles and income.

Conclusions:¶

  • TM195

    • It appears to be the low end of the product range and targets users with an average income of ~ 46418, and an income range between 30000 and 50000
    • Generally preferred by people between 20 and 30 years of age.
    • Single males tend to prefer TM195 over the other models.
    • Partnered females strongly prefer the TM195 and partnered males prefer it at nearly the same level as they prefer the TM498.

  • TM498

    • This appears to be the mid-range or 'better' category product but appears to target the same group as the TM195.
    • Ideally, this product would target consumers with average fitness/usage levels of around 3.7 or 3.8 and income levels on average of about 60000 (between the average levels of TM195 and TM798). However, it fails to do this.
    • The product appeals to single females. This should be explored further by looking at the features relative to TM195 and understanding the Voice of the Customer (VOC) better.

  • TM798

    • This product has the least sales volume and attempts to target the highest income, education, fitness, miles, and usage levels amongst users.
    • The opportunity to extend the uptake of this product amongst 30 - 40 year olds, and amongst females in particular needs to be explored as females do not seem to prefer this product for some reason.
    • The possibility of extending the sales of this product to people with lower fitness, usage, and mileage profiles needs to be investigated.
